The basic functional unit of skeletal muscle tissue is the individual muscle cell. This cell contains several distinct regions, including a nucleus, mitochondria, and sarcoplasm. The sarcoplasm is the fluid matrix inside the cell, and consists of cytoplasm, myofibrils, and sarcoplasmic reticulum. The sarcoplasm is separated from the extracellular space by the cell membrane. The cytoplasm is the region inside the cell. It contains enzymes and other cell organelles. The mitochondria are organelles that generate energy for the cell. All proteins absorb electromagnetic radiation of wavelength around 190 nm which is in UV range. The absorption of light by proteins causes excitation of electrons from ground state to excited state. The electrons in excited state are unstable and tend to return to ground state. This return to ground state is termed as relaxation. The lifetime of electrons in excited state is in the order of pico seconds. The relaxation of electrons from excited state to ground state is nonradiative. Y2K means ‘Year 2000’. The term Y2K is used to describe a problem in computer programming, whereby computers which store years as two digits (e.g. ’98’), cannot distinguish between the years ’00’ and ’01’. As 2000 is the first year to have 4 digits, many computers will interpret it as ’1900’.
